More than anything, this year feels like a reset, a turbulent intermission =
between the last act and the next. And I couldn=E2=80=99t be more excited f=
or what=E2=80=99s on deck.=20
I=E2=80=99m taking the next few weeks off =E2=80=94 I=E2=80=99ll be back in=
 your inbox January 9th =E2=80=94 and the time off for the new year means a=
 chance to pause, read, reflect,  and kick off 2023 with a fresh blank page=
=2E This one=E2=80=99s about how I=E2=80=99m going to fill it in.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Blank Page
During nearly every week of the past three years, at some point, I=E2=80=99=
ve stared at my laptop and my laptop has stared back at me, like this:=C2=
=A0
Not to brag, but I=E2=80=99ve become somewhat of an expert in staring down =
blank pages.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s what to do when one faces you:=C2=A0
Panic. This is an unavoidable part of the process, so embrace it.=C2=A0
Type. You might not know what you want to say. That=E2=80=99s OK. Start typ=
ing.
Delete. Whatever you just typed was probably shit. Delete it. It=E2=80=99s =
OK, too.=C2=A0
Scroll. Twitter, TikTok, Substack, Reader. Wherever you find ideas, head th=
ere.=C2=A0
Read. You found some interesting stuff. Read it. Save it. Highlight it. Tak=
e notes.
Sit/Walk/Run. Let the ideas simmer in a clear head, free from distraction.
Listen. OK, maybe throw on a podcast related to your vague idea and half-li=
sten.=C2=A0
Title. You might have the beginning of a topic now. Write the title down.=
=C2=A0
Immerse. Soak in as much as you possibly can on topics related to your titl=
e.=C2=A0
Talk. Talk to people who are knowledgeable about what you=E2=80=99re thinki=
ng through.
Skim. Skim your notes/highlights/whatever from what you=E2=80=99ve read and=
 listened to.=C2=A0
Intro. Like picking a line on a ski slope. Nail it, and the rest becomes ea=
sier.
Keep Typing. If the intro=E2=80=99s momentum carries you, type as much as y=
ou can.
Read More. Fill in your knowledge gaps by reading to answer specific questi=
ons.=C2=A0
Sit/Walk/Run. You need a break. All that skimming, reading, and typing. Whe=
w.
Type More. Get back to your keyboard, open your Doc, type. Try not to edit =
yet.=C2=A0
Edit. OK, edit now. Read for flow. Cut things that sound dumb. Find holes.=
=C2=A0
Rejigger. Fill in those holes, move things around, rewrite sentences.=C2=A0
Art. Add images where useful. Note: this is also a good way to procrastinat=
e.=C2=A0
Share. Send whatever you=E2=80=99ve written to someone you trust to give ha=
rd feedback.=C2=A0
Polish. Take that person=E2=80=99s feedback and incorporate the good bits i=
nto your piece.
Sleep. Sleep on it. This whole thing may take days, you may sleep a few tim=
es.
Re-read. Go over everything once again. You=E2=80=99ll find things that no =
longer work.
Re-intro. Given everything you=E2=80=99ve done since Step 12, your intro mi=
ght be stale.
Tweak. Make those last adjustments. Confirm it=E2=80=99s all as just-right =
as it will be.
Send. If you=E2=80=99re going public with the piece, hit send. Otherwise, s=
quirrel it away.=C2=A0
Tweet. Let the people know you defeated the blank page and wrote a thing.=
=C2=A0
Hide. Try not to read too many of the replies.=C2=A0
Rest. Get away from your computer. Read. Drink. Watch a dumb show. Sleep.
Restart. Go back to Step 1. Stare down a brand new blank page.=C2=A0
Everyone=E2=80=99s process is a little different. The pro bloggers, the one=
s who do it every day, skip steps, just bang it out. The true writers might=
 take months or years and end up with a beautifully-written novel. There ar=
e many flavors in between. That=E2=80=99s the process that I unintentionall=
y follow most of the time, and it works well enough, as much as I would lik=
e it to work better.
A blank page can feel like a curse. It often feels like a curse. But a new =
one can also be a relief. By the time you=E2=80=99re finished whatever you =
filled that last blank page in with, you might have come to hate it, or at =
least gotten sick of it. I can go so deep on a topic, get so far into it, t=
hat halfway through I wonder if it=E2=80=99s the best or most important or =
most interesting thing I could be writing about, but by then, it=E2=80=99s =
too late. I=E2=80=99m in too deep.=C2=A0
And so the blank page is a chance to start fresh, to really write the best =
or most important or most interesting thing I possibly can, free from the s=
unk cost and (ever-so-temporarily) relieved from the pressures of a deadlin=
e.=C2=A0
This isn=E2=80=99t an essay about writing an essay, though.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a *metaphor*.
Every new year is a blank page, a chance to start fresh with new ideas and =
new sources and new energy. Of course, January 1st isn=E2=80=99t actually a=
ny more different from December 31st than December 31st was from December 3=
0th. But the collective time we all spend away from the daily routine durin=
g the holidays feels like a reset. And we=E2=80=99ve all tacitly agreed tha=
t the new year is a different thing than the old year. So it=E2=80=99s clos=
e enough to actually different.=C2=A0
This particular upcoming new year feels even more different, like a decadal=
 reset.=C2=A0
Markets have crashed (optimistically) or are in the process of crashing (re=
alistically). The wave of momentum that the tech industry has been riding s=
ince the early 2010s has crashed (optimistically) or is in the process of c=
rashing (realistically).=C2=A0
The past few years have been chaotic and weird, and it came to a boiling po=
int in 2022. The things that made sense a couple of years ago, the sure thi=
ngs, don=E2=80=99t make as much sense, are no longer sure. You might be exp=
eriencing the weird as a general vibe or very specifically in your life and=
 career.=C2=A0
So Step 1: Panic.=C2=A0
But if you=E2=80=99ve been reading Not Boring this year, or the two before =
it, you know this isn=E2=80=99t really about how scary things are, or how s=
cary they=E2=80=99ll be. It=E2=80=99s just a blank page, and blank pages ar=
e opportunities, if you take them to be. We=E2=80=99re optimists here, so l=
et=E2=80=99s take them that way.=C2=A0
One of the inspirations for this piece =E2=80=93 Step 4: Scroll, Step 5: Re=
ad =E2=80=93 was an essay I came across in Noah Smith=E2=80=99s interview w=
ith Ezra Klein [ https://substack.com/redirect/f78a46fa-8c35-466b-9cac-2777=
f804799b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]. Klein said of the post-Elon-Twitter-internet-landscape, =E2=80=9CMaybe =
it=E2=80=99s also an opportunity. I=E2=80=99m inspired by Robin Sloan=E2=80=
=99s call [ https://substack.com/redirect/e79f7bbb-b456-4391-ab9b-d84bca47a=
83e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to=
 make this a season of experimentation in how I use the internet, and what =
I use my energy to help bring into existence on the internet.=E2=80=9D Clic=
k [ https://substack.com/redirect/e79f7bbb-b456-4391-ab9b-d84bca47a83e?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s my exhortation,=E2=80=9D Sloan exhorted:
Let 2023 be a year of exper=C2=ADi=C2=ADmen=C2=ADta=C2=ADtion and invention=
!
Let it come from the edges, the margins, the provinces, the marshes!
THIS MEANS YOU!
I am thinking specif=C2=ADi=C2=ADcally of exper=C2=ADi=C2=ADmen=C2=ADta=C2=
=ADtion around =E2=80=9Cways of relating online=E2=80=9D. I=E2=80=99ve used=
 that phrase before, and I acknowl=C2=ADedge it might be a bit obscure=E2=
=80=89=E2=80=A6=E2=80=89but, for me, it captures the rich overlap of publis=
hing and networking, media and conviviality. It=E2=80=99s this domain that =
was so deci=C2=ADsively captured in the 2010s, and it=E2=80=99s this domain=
 that is newly up for grabs.
It is 2003 again. Facebook, Twitter, and Insta=C2=ADgram haven=E2=80=99t be=
en invented yet=E2=80=89=E2=80=A6=E2=80=89except, it=E2=80=99s also 2023, a=
nd they have, so you can learn from their rise and ruin.
Sloan is calling for experimentation in how we relate online, not how we do=
 everything (although the two are moving closer and closer [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/d4f867ff-87a5-4df8-ac99-c725e664b95d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]).=C2=A0
If Twitter is toxic, great, go play with smaller communities. If it=E2=80=
=99s too shallow, start a book club. If Facebook has gotten too crowded to =
be fun, cultivate smaller group chats with friends new and old. If you scro=
ll Instagram too much, stop.=C2=A0
My personal opinion is that the next decade in online experiences will be d=
riven by smaller, more niche, more tailored products =E2=80=93 we won=E2=80=
=99t see a social media app born this decade cross a $1 trillion market cap=
, like Facebook did, briefly =E2=80=93 but that=E2=80=99s just my opinion. =
If re-reading the past two years=E2=80=99 year-end posts have taught me any=
thing, it=E2=80=99s that predictions are hard and mine are often wrong. If =
you want to build products online, bring your own opinion and influence the=
 outcomes of your predictions.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99d go wider than Sloan, though. I think 2023 is the start of somet=
hing entirely new. If I could add a personal exhortation, by subtracting, I=
 would exhort:
Let 2023 be a year of exper=C2=ADi=C2=ADmen=C2=ADta=C2=ADtion and invention=
!
Let it come from the edges, the margins, the provinces, the marshes!
THIS MEANS YOU!
More boldly: Choose Good Quests [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d49f841-9a=
ab-44af-a292-f356d487bb13?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Click.=C2=A0
In the most simple terms possible: a good quest makes the future better tha=
n our world today, while a bad quest doesn't improve the world much at all,=
 or even makes it worse.
The essay=E2=80=99s co-authors, Trae Stephens [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/095ef249-fb03-45cf-b981-8d028ecdec29?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Markie Wagner [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/ed058baf-f7ad-4794-89a4-54ddabb691f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] name a bunch of Good Quests:
Reversing aging, going to Mars, curing cancer, building a supersonic plane,=
 creating AGI, or founding a new country=E2=80=A6
semiconductor manufacturing, complex industrial automation, natural resourc=
e discovery, next-generation energy production, low-cost and low-labor cons=
truction, new modes of transportation, general artificial intelligence, map=
ping and interfacing with the brain, extending the human lifespan.
These are massive, humanity-altering things, and there are more besides thi=
s, some of which I listed in Decentralization [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/656761fa-3ac0-44d3-a0e9-be744e20cef9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Everything is up for grabs.
These are the quests that bend that oscillating sine curve upwards. A big t=
heme in Not Boring in 2022 is that those quests, while still painfully diff=
icult, are more possible and financially viable today than they have ever b=
een.=C2=A0
Why? I=E2=80=99ve become enamored by the exponential curves that drive indu=
stries.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s the OG, Moore=E2=80=99s Law:
And the declining cost of solar:
And the declining cost of sequencing the human genome:
(Hint: if those curves don=E2=80=99t look exponential at first glance, look=
 at the y-axes.)
You=E2=80=99ve probably seen these charts. I=E2=80=99ve included all of the=
m in Not Boring posts at one point or another, and other people talk about =
them a lot too. What=E2=80=99s most fascinating to me about them is that wh=
ile they look inevitable, like math, they require the efforts of thousands =
or millions of people to stay on track.=C2=A0
Albert Einstein said that =E2=80=9CCompound interest is the eighth wonder o=
f the world,=E2=80=9D but with all due respect, compound interest just happ=
ens. It=E2=80=99s contracts and math. The curves above are the real eighth =
wonder. Somehow, over the years, the invisibly-directed efforts of a bunch =
of people, each contributing their unique and varied skills, somehow, wondr=
ously, resulted in smooth, exponential curves.=C2=A0
In The Invisible Hand=E2=80=99s Visible Swarm [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/b0fb35ad-1cf0-435f-a595-80dcaac25741?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I tried to square that emergent mystery:
Individual actions matter deeply, but given enough time, the free market is=
 shockingly good at directing those individuals=E2=80=99 actions and money =
at tackling the right really hard problems.
I got so close to fitting this whole essay in the email. To read the last ~=
900 words of Not Boring for 2022=E2=80=A6=20
